@TechReport{	  Dahen:2007aa,
  abstract	= {According to Basel II criteria, the use of external data
		  is absolutely indispensable to the implementation of an
		  advanced method for calculating operational capital. This
		  article investigates how the severity and frequencies of
		  external losses are scaled for integration with internal
		  data. We set up an initial model designed to explain the
		  loss severity. This model takes into account firm size,
		  location, and business lines as well as risk types. It also
		  shows how to calculate the internal loss equivalent to an
		  external loss, which might occur in a given bank. OLS
		  estimation results show that the above variables have
		  significant power in explaining the loss amount. They are
		  used to develop a normalization formula. A second model
		  based on external data is developed to scale the frequency
		  of losses over a given period. Two regression models are
		  analyzed: the truncated Poisson model and the truncated
		  negative binomial model. Variables estimating the size and
		  geographical distribution of the banks' activities have
		  been introduced as explanatory variables. The results show
		  that the negative binomial distribution outperforms the
		  Poisson distribution. The scaling is done by calculating
		  the parameters of the selected distribution based on the
		  estimated coefficients and the variables related to a given
		  bank. Frequency of losses of more than $1 million are
		  generated on a specific horizon.},
